</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34950FAFFA7FFDAFF12F9B6DF53DCC0" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BEC0371FFA7FFDAFF12F9B6D810DE45" blockId="17.[123,651,1454,1741]" lastBlockId="17.[699,1228,193,1331]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">OTHER MATERIAL: A single specimen (AMNH 63844) labeled ‘‘Guamanı´’’ on one side of the original label and ‘‘Cerro Guamanı´’’ on the other side was collected by the Olallas in 1922. Additional shrews from the Cordillera Oriental include one (MCN 150) collected at Papallacta by C. Olalla in 1931 and another (QCAZ 307) collected on Antisana by R. Sierra in 1985 (D. Tirira, personal commun.).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEC0371FFA7FFDAFD52FEA4DF53DCC0" blockId="17.[699,1228,193,1331]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
TAXONOMY: The Ecuadorean species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5378F2FFA7FFDAFD31FEC6D80EDE1E" box="[699,807,340,363]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Cryptotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B927DF63FFA7FFDAFD31FEC6D80EDE1E" box="[699,807,340,363]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Cryptotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were recently reviewed by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC27E80FFA7FFDAFBE7FEC6D819DEFD" author="Vivar, E. &amp; V. Pacheco &amp; M. Valqui" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 15" refId="ref25611" refString="Vivar, E., V. Pacheco, and M. Valqui. 1997. A new species of Cryptotis (Insectivora: Soricidae) from northern Peru. American Museum Novitates 3202: 1 - 15." type="journal article" year="1997">Vivar et al. (1997)</bibRefCitation>
, who identified the Guamaní specimen (AMNH 63844) as 
<taxonomicName id="4C5378F2FFA7FFDAFC6FFE1DDFA7DED3" baseAuthorityName="Anthony" baseAuthorityYear="1921" box="[997,1166,399,422]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Cryptotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="montivagus">
<emphasis id="B927DF63FFA7FFDAFC6FFE1DDFA7DED3" box="[997,1166,399,422]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">C. montivagus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The five Papallacta shrews, collected only a few kilometers from Guamanı´, appear to be indistinguishable from AMNH 63844 and presumably represent the same taxon. However, measurements of these 
<specimenCount id="9D55C8F8FFA7FFDAFC5DFDB3DF57DD4D" box="[983,1150,545,568]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="generic">six specimens</specimenCount>
(from Papallacta and Guamanı´) indicate that they have slightly narrower zygomatic plates and broader interorbits than typical 
<taxonomicName id="4C5378F2FFA7FFDAFBB4FDEBDFEDDDE5" baseAuthorityName="Anthony" baseAuthorityYear="1921" box="[1086,1220,633,656]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Cryptotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="montivagus">
<emphasis id="B927DF63FFA7FFDAFBB4FDEBDFEDDDE5" box="[1086,1220,633,656]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">montivagus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and side­by­side comparisons reveal that they have much less robust anterior unicuspids than any specimen of the 
<typeStatus id="54E8BDD3FFA7FFDAFBC3FD43DF52DD9D" box="[1097,1147,721,744]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">type</typeStatus>
series (AMNH 47197–47201; from Bestión, in the Ecuadorean province of 
<collectingRegion id="4997CD93FFA7FFDAFC6FFC9EDF1FDC56" box="[997,1078,780,803]" country="Ecuador" name="Azuay" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Azuay</collectingRegion>
). The possible taxonomic significance of these and other differences (V. Pacheco and N. Woodman, personal commun.) remain to be determined by a more comprehensive evaluation of character variation in Ecuadorean shrews.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34950FAFFA7FFDAFD52FC2EDFA1DA46" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BEC0371FFA7FFDAFD52FC2ED8AFDB5E" blockId="17.[699,1228,193,1331]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
REMARKS: In a previous list of Papallacta mammals (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC27E80FFA7FFDAFCB4FC4BD8EEDC85" author="Voss, R. S." box="[830,967,985,1008]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="259 - 493" refId="ref25650" refString="Voss, R. S. 1988. Systematics and ecology of ichthyomyine rodents (Muroidea): patterns of morphological evolution in a small adaptive radiation. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 188: 259 - 493." type="journal article" year="1988">Voss, 1988</bibRefCitation>
: table 43), I misidentified this material as 
<taxonomicName id="4C5378F2FFA7FFDAFC6FFC65D8ABDB5E" authority="(Merriam, 1897)" baseAuthorityName="Merriam" baseAuthorityYear="1897" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Cryptotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="thomasi">
<emphasis id="B927DF63FFA7FFDAFC6FFC65DFE5DB7B" box="[997,1228,1015,1038]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Cryptotis thomasi</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC27E80FFA7FFDAFD49FB86D853DB5E" author="Merriam, C. H." box="[707,890,1044,1067]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="227 - 230" refId="ref23852" refString="Merriam, C. H. 1897. Descriptions of five new shrews from Mexico, Guatemala, and Colombia. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington 11: 227 - 230." type="journal article" year="1897">Merriam, 1897</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEC0371FFA7FFDAFD52FBA3DFA1DA46" blockId="17.[699,1228,193,1331]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
FIELD OBSERVATIONS: The five shrews that I collected near Papallacta in 1980 were taken at elevations ranging from 
<quantity id="4CABAE94FFA7FFDAFBA0FBFED9FCDBD5" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.6149999999999998" metricValueMax="3.66" metricValueMin="3.57" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="m" value="3615.0" valueMax="3660.0" valueMin="3570.0">3570 to 3660 m</quantity>
. Of these, three were trapped on the ground in runways or small tunnels through moss in Subalpine Rain Forest, one was found dead on a trail in Subalpine Rain Forest, and one was trapped in a runway though tall grass at the páramo/forest ecotone.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
